CLASSICAL SWINE FEVER - LATVIA: (BALTINAVA, DAGDA) PORCINE AND WILD BOAR, UPDATE
********************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: Thu 26 Jun 2014
Source: The Baltic Course [edited]
http://www.baltic-course.com/eng/markets_and_companies/?doc=93229


On [22 Jun 2014] classical swine fever was detected on a farm in Dagda municipality (southeastern Latvia), reports LETA/Nozare.lv.

The Food and Veterinary Service representative Anna Joffe informed the business portal Nozare.lv that 3 cases of swine fever in wild boar had been registered in the region so far this year [2014]. Wild boar in this region have been regularly vaccinated against swine fever since 2013.

A total of 8 pigs were culled and cremated on the farm; disinfection has been carried out as well.

On [26 Nov 2012], swine fever was ascertained on 3 farms in Latgale [region in eastern Latvia]; 14 infected pigs were killed and disinfection was carried out, and the pig owners received compensation. No new cases of swine fever have been registered on Latvian farms since. In 2013, laboratory tests established 46 cases of swine fever in wild boars.

